John Edward: Knowledge of languages essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence. This has continued in 2018 with further outstanding exam results and is only supported by individual and joint achievements in the fields of sport, art, music and other community-based enterprises.
With more than 30,000 pupils from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest possible level of care for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak with someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak with him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current review results of this year show that languages with the highest rates of survival are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who learned foreign languages achieved grade A in the higher exams.
The data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of the students in Mandarin achieved Note A in the higher exams, while 72 percent of the students learning German, 69 percent of the students learning French, and 63 percent of the students learning Spanish also achieved Note A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered as subjects of choice as well as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and other places.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for the problems of filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more open jobs require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage through such a lifelong ability in the future.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 percent did not speak well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today's children that we now invest in language lessons.
Children who speak several languages, in particular the languages of developing countries, will have better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom with a view to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese, will be taught.
Wherever your child's interests lie, independent schools will always be able to choose a number of languages with appropriate specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need for their success, as the future always looks like.
At this point in time, in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain essential to the future of the country. Therefore, this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as 'international communication'.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
We have to do it.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
