North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's Foreign Minister said on Saturday before the United Nations that continued sanctions deepened their distrust of the United States and that under these circumstances the country would not give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho said to the annual General Assembly of the World Organisation that North Korea had, last year, taken "essential steps" on the basis of good will. For example, it stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear test site and undertook not to increase nuclear weapons and technologies.
"We do not see a corresponding reaction from the US," he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security, and in these circumstances we will in no way be unilateral first."
While Ri was familiar with North Korea’s complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phase” approach to denucleization, where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denucleization from the outset as it had done in the past by Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit meeting between a US President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June. In this, Kim had assured him to work on the "denucleization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump offered guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea is aiming for an official end to the Korean war between 1950 and 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongjang must first give up his nuclear weapons.
Washington also opposes calls for a relaxation of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'first denucleization' and increases pressure by sanctions to reach its goal by force, and is even opposed to the 'clarification of the end of war'," said Ri.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us into our knees is a brain-spin of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not go into plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. Head of State had emphasized at the UN at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea's head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea were the other party to the denucleization issue instead of the US, the denucleization of the Korean peninsula would not have brought about this halt."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech differed greatly from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the mainland of the United States with North Korea rockets after "the evil president" Trump Kim had called "the rocket man" on suicide mission.
This year Trump, who had threatened with the “full destruction” of North Korea last year, overtook Kim at the United Nations with praise for his courage to take disarmament steps. However, he said there was still much work to be done and the sanctions had to remain in force until the denucleization of North Korea.
On Wednesday, Trump said that he had no time frame for it: "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months – doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said to the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The enforcement of the Security Council's sanctions must definitely continue vigorously until we have achieved complete, final and verified denuklearisation."
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry out Pyongyang's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri at the margins of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongjang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not successful.
In July, when he left Pjongjang, he said that progress had been made only to be accused by North Korea hours later of having made "gait-like demands".
North Korea promised this month at a meeting with Moon, to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear complex when the United States took 'acceptable measures'.
He said that Kim had told him that the 'corresponding measures' were security guarantees that Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn in a course, enough to sleep
A new course at Harvard University will make sure that all students get more sleep during their basic studies this year. This is a measure against the growing macho culture to keep up with caffeine and learn all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world's leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to paying attention to themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is, in his opinion, the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after having given a lecture on the effects of withdrawal from sleep on learning.
“ At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘ Why do I experience it only now, in my last year? ’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is. That surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
This year's course for the first time explained to the students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Managing Director of the University's Health Services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it had found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, the students see the image of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They receive information on the effects of caffeine and light as well as on the effects of lack of sleep on the sporty performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep withdrawal can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged by means of a map of the university campus with interactive symbols to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know – just like you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride in pushing a "night shift" was still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep a growing problem.
To ensure good sleep, he said the "secret weapon" of all students should be against stress, exhaustion and anxiety. Furthermore, it would be possible to avoid weight gain, as sleep withdrawal would put the brain in starvation, so that it would be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course. Last year he had completed one of his courses in Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to press for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study program before they start their studies at the competition-oriented university.
