HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14% in the number of people living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people are affected in the country.
Approximately 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
In contrast to the past, the transfer took place in the vast majority of new cases through sex.
To date, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people thus infected with HIV had been reduced to almost zero, and Chinese health officials gave up at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, by year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
HIV transmission by sex is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against members of the LGBT community is to be widespread.
Based on the country's conservative values, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men ultimately marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are due to insufficient protection of sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has been promising, among other things, general access to HIV medicines to address the problem.
