National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
In an estate in the highlands of Scotland, new research is being carried out to show how bats use the landscape to search for food.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insight into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to guide future nature conservation activities.
The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track dwarfs and mosquitoes, as well as the brown Langohr and water fleas in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
In a sound analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and which species does what.
A map and a report of the habitat will then be created to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
These data will help to determine the benefits of the measures for the management of the habitat, such as the creation of meadows, and to show how forest areas can be preserved for bats and other related species.
The stocks of bats in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to loss of habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-catchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo location to detect insects and obstacles in their runway.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across Scotland, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out examinations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even set up Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for her.
"Here in Threave we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there are many things we don't know about bats yet, which is why we are doing these works here and in other goods, which will help us to learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stressed the importance of excluding the presence of bats before maintenance in the goods, since it was possible that the accidental destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and extinguish the entire population on site.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and we do not know how many of our species are concerned with their populations."
