Why Beijing could benefit from the US-China trade war
The opening halls of the trade war between the US and China were deafening. Although the battle is not over for a long time, Beijing could benefit from a long-term pit between the countries, my expert.
Donald Trump, the American President, fired the first warning at the beginning of the year when he was serving important Chinese export goods, including solar cells, steel and aluminium, with penalty tariffs.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new customs duties on goods worth 200 billion dollars, which effectively affects half of all goods imported from China into the USA.
Beijing fell in the same way each time and recently raised fines from five to ten percent on American goods worth 60 billion dollars.
China vows to respond to any action taken by the US and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economic power will soon collapse.
To move Washington to lead would mean to give up. However, a public cut to the US would be far too shameful for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that, if Beijing plays out its cards well, China could benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
