Syria be 'ready' for the return of refugees, according to the Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country that has been devastated by the war for over seven years.
In an address before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that circumstances in the country improved.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government rebuilds the areas destroyed by terrorists to allow normality to return.
All conditions were now set for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed aid for the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional assistance from countries that supported the uprising.
