Update to the Red Age: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more incomplete flowering conditions are recorded, indicating falling concentrations.
A red algae flower extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinella to the south of the district of Lee.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough, but less than last week.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
In the last week, medium concentrations were reported on or off the coast of Pinella District, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee District, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Charlotte District, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee District, and low concentrations in the district of Collier.
Respiratory complaints are still reported from the districts of Pinella, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No new respiratory problems have been reported in Northwestern Florida during the last week.
